## Diagnosis

The `micro` rendering mode was introduced as a well-intentioned "fit everything in" solution for small tiles (32–64px wide), but it produces unreadable 8px text. The fundamental error is that the component is trying to render *content* at any size rather than *suppressing* content below a legibility threshold.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — "Shrink to fit" anti-pattern**: scaling typography down to match a container instead of hiding content that cannot be rendered legibly. Text below ~11px is effectively illegible for most users and fails WCAG 1.4.4 (Resize Text) in spirit.

The micro mode likely looks something like this in the component:

```tsx
// KnowledgeTreemap.tsx  ← the offending branch
const tileMode =
  width < 32  ? 'hidden'  :
  width < 64  ? 'micro'   :   // ← AP-072: shrinks text to 8px
  width < 120 ? 'compact' :
                'full';
```

```tsx
{tileMode === 'micro' && (
  <span className="text-[8px] leading-none truncate">{category.name}</span>
)}
```

---

## Fix

### 1. Remove the `micro` mode entirely — suppress, don't shrink

**`components/knowledge/KnowledgeTreemap.tsx`**

```tsx
// BEFORE
const tileMode =
  width < 32  ? 'hidden'  :
  width < 64  ? 'micro'   :
  width < 120 ? 'compact' :
                'full';
```

```tsx
// AFTER — 'micro' removed; small tiles are simply silent
const tileMode =
  width < 64  ? 'hidden'  :
  width < 120 ? 'compact' :
                'full';
```

### 2. Remove the micro render branch

```tsx
// BEFORE
{tileMode === 'hidden' && null}

{tileMode === 'micro' && (
  <span className="text-[8px] leading-none truncate">
    {category.name}
  </span>
)}

{tileMode === 'compact' && (
  <span className="text-xs leading-tight truncate">
    {category.name}
  </span>
)}

{tileMode === 'full' && (
  <>
    <span className="text-sm font-medium leading-snug">{category.name}</span>
    <span className="text-xs text-secondary">{category.count} items</span>
  </>
)}
```

```tsx
// AFTER
{/* tiles < 64px wide: render nothing — colour alone carries the meaning */}
{tileMode === 'hidden' && null}

{tileMode === 'compact' && (
  <span className="text-xs leading-tight truncate">
    {category.name}
  </span>
)}

{tileMode === 'full' && (
  <>
    <span className="text-sm font-medium leading-snug">{category.name}</span>
    <span className="text-xs text-secondary">{category.count} items</span>
  </>
)}
```

### 3. Ensure hidden tiles still communicate meaning via colour + tooltip

Small tiles carry information through their fill colour and a tooltip — add `title` so the name is still accessible:

```tsx
// The tile wrapper — always present regardless of tileMode
<div
  className={cn(
    'relative overflow-hidden rounded-sm transition-opacity',
    'hover:opacity-80 focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring',
    tile.colorClass,
  )}
  style={{ width, height }}
  title={category.name}          // ← accessible name on every tile
  aria-label={category.name}
  role="img"
>
  {/* text only rendered when space is sufficient */}
  {tileMode === 'compact' && (
    <span className="text-xs leading-tight truncate px-1 pt-0.5 block">
      {category.name}
    </span>
  )}
  {tileMode === 'full' && (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-0.5 p-1.5">
      <span className="text-sm font-medium leading-snug">{category.name}</span>
      <span className="text-xs text-secondary">{category.count} items</span>
    </div>
  )}
</div>
```

---

## The Principle

> **Content below its legibility threshold should be suppressed, not compressed.**

When a container is too small to render text at its minimum legible size, the correct response is to hide the text and rely on the next available affordance (colour, tooltip, hover state, zoom). Never scale type below the design system's smallest defined size (`text-xs` / 12px in Tailwind's default scale, or whatever `--text-xs` resolves to in your Elan tokens).

Concretely:

| Container width | Text strategy |
|---|---|
| < 64px | No text. Colour + `title`/tooltip only |
| 64–119px | `text-xs` (12px) truncated label |
| ≥ 120px | Full label + metadata |

The threshold numbers are design-system constants — put them in one place:

```ts
// lib/treemap-constants.ts
export const TREEMAP_THRESHOLDS = {
  silent:  64,   // px — below this: no text
  compact: 120,  // px — below this: label only
} as const;
```

Import them in the component and in any future treemap variants so the rule is enforced at the source, not rediscovered per-component.
